Practice 1

Medley and Clements (1998) sampled a number of stations (between four and seven) on six streams known to be polluted by heavy metals in the Rocky Mountain Region of Colorado. They recorded zinc concentration, species diversity of the diatom community, and the name of each stream.

medley.csv file contents:

stream - name of streams in the Rocky Mountain region of Colorado, USA

zinc_level - categorical zinc concentration level (HIGH=high, MED=medium, LOW=low, BACK=background)

diversity - Shannon-Wiener species diversity of diatoms

reference_number - alternative categorical zinc concentration level (1=background, 2=low, 3=medium, 4=high)

Using the medley.csv data set,

  1. Determine whether the mean diatom species diversity differs across the four zinc-level groups

  2. Determine whether different levels of zinc pollution differ in their effect on diatom species diversity

  3. Present a bar chart figure depicting means and standard errors for the four levels of pollution.

  4. Arrange the bars to proceed in ascending order of pollution (B < L < M < H). Hint, after importing the data, immediately change the order of factor levels (the default is alphabetical, but that doesn’t make sense here).

#Reorder the factor levels to be more intuitive.
medley$zinc_level <- factor(medley$zinc_level, levels = c('BACK', 'LOW', 'MED', 'HIGH'))
#check to make sure they were reordered
unique(medley$zinc_level)
## [1] LOW  MED  BACK HIGH
## Levels: BACK LOW MED HIGH

Start by visualizing the data, easiest methods are a point plot and a box plot (doesn’t require you to summarize data first).

These figures don’t actually help visualize differences all that much, especially because there are some potential outliers that are tricking our eye and no error bars to help visually determine pairwise group differences. Lets summarize the data so we can display the means and error bars. If your levels of zinc are in a different order (such as alphabetical), then you didn’t properly re-level the categorical zinc_level variable.

## # A tibble: 4 × 5
##   zinc_level  mean     n    sd    se
##   <fct>      <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 BACK        1.80     8 0.485 0.172
## 2 LOW         2.03     8 0.445 0.157
## 3 MED         1.72     9 0.503 0.168
## 4 HIGH        1.28     9 0.427 0.142

Now that we have summary statistics for the medley data set, we can make a more informative figure.

That is much more helpful because we can clearly see both the means and standard errors to infer pairwise differences among stream types. The HIGH concentration zinc streams clearly have lower species diversity than the others. First we need to fit a linear model to see whether there are overall differences among stream types.

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = diversity ~ zinc_level, data = medley)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -1.03750 -0.22896  0.07986  0.33222  0.79750 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)     1.79750    0.16478  10.909 5.81e-12 ***
## zinc_levelLOW   0.23500    0.23303   1.008   0.3213    
## zinc_levelMED  -0.07972    0.22647  -0.352   0.7273    
## zinc_levelHIGH -0.51972    0.22647  -2.295   0.0289 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.4661 on 30 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2826, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2108 
## F-statistic: 3.939 on 3 and 30 DF,  p-value: 0.01756

From the ANOVA report at the bottom, there appears to be overall differences (p = 0.017) in diversity among the streams with different concentrations of zinc. This indicates that at least one stream is significantly different from the others in species diversity (reject null hypothesis that all stream types have the same diversity).

Now we use the emmeans package to make pairwise comparisons among the four stream types.

##  contrast    estimate    SE df t.ratio p.value
##  BACK - LOW   -0.2350 0.233 30  -1.008  0.7457
##  BACK - MED    0.0797 0.226 30   0.352  0.9847
##  BACK - HIGH   0.5197 0.226 30   2.295  0.1219
##  LOW - MED     0.3147 0.226 30   1.390  0.5153
##  LOW - HIGH    0.7547 0.226 30   3.333  0.0117
##  MED - HIGH    0.4400 0.220 30   2.003  0.2096
## 
## P value adjustment: tukey method for comparing a family of 4 estimates

It looks like the only significant difference in species diversity was between the LOW and HIGH zinc streams (p = 0.011). Lets do a quick plot to visualize this difference. Yep, no overlap between error bars of LOW and HIGH groups.

Now we can try to describe all pairwise comparisons among groups ourselves, or we can use a Connecting Letters Differences (CLD) report to help.

##  zinc_level emmean    SE df lower.CL upper.CL .group
##  HIGH         1.28 0.155 30    0.961     1.60  a    
##  MED          1.72 0.155 30    1.401     2.04  ab   
##  BACK         1.80 0.165 30    1.461     2.13  ab   
##  LOW          2.03 0.165 30    1.696     2.37   b   
## 
## Confidence level used: 0.95 
## P value adjustment: tukey method for comparing a family of 4 estimates 
## significance level used: alpha = 0.05 
## NOTE: Compact letter displays can be misleading
##       because they show NON-findings rather than findings.
##       Consider using 'pairs()', 'pwpp()', or 'pwpm()' instead.

Transcribe the group letters onto the bar chart you made previously. Be careful, the multcomp package does not respect the reordering of levels you did previously; it sorts groups by lowest to highest mean. Transcribe letters carefully.

(Sidenote: Can you think of a way of forcing R to sort the CLD report by your re-leveled zinc_level variable rather than by the default of increasing emmean?)

If you previously made the chart an object (like you should always do) then it will be easy to call up here and add text annotations or text boxes depicting differences among streams.

p1 +
  annotate("text", x=4, y=1.5, label="a") +    #HIGH
  annotate("text", x=3, y=2, label="a,b") +    #MED
  annotate("text", x=1, y=2.25, label="a,b") + #BACK
  annotate("text", x=2, y=2.25, label="b") +  #LOW
  #make plot pretty
  xlab("Zinc Level") +
  ylab("Diatom Species Diversity") +
  theme_bw()

Practice 2

Using the ChickWeight data set built into R, test the hypothesis that diet type influences growth (and therefore weight) of chicks. Call the ChickWeight data set and notice that the data are a time-series; multiple measurements of each chick taken across different time periods. Because these data are therefore not independent (one of our assumptions) it will be necessary to reduce the data set to one that is. Use only the final measurements for each chick (n=50 chicks at Time=21) and discard the others (we then have one measurement of each chick).

ChickWeight <- ChickWeight %>%
  filter(Time == 21)

Practice 3

Basil is one of the world most important commercial herbs. Like many herbaceous species, basil has several desirable compounds used by humans. Basildiol is the active ingredient in basil that gives the distinct bite and aroma. You are working for a commercial lab interested in extracting the maximum basildiol and you have three candidate strains.

Is there an overall difference among strains?

Are there pairwise differences between the strains?

## # A tibble: 3 × 5
